Find the angles of the triangle whose sides are $3 + \sqrt{3},$ $2 \sqrt{3},$ and $\sqrt{6}.$  Enter the angles of the triangle, measured in degrees, separated by commas.
inference:
By the Law of Cosines, we have

$$\begin{aligned} (3 + \sqrt{3})^2 &= 2 \sqrt{3}^2 + \sqrt{6}^2 - 2 \cdot 2 \sqrt{3} \cdot \sqrt{6} \cos A \\\ 17 + 6 \sqrt{3} &= 12 + 6 - 12 \sqrt{3} \cos A \\\ 12 \sqrt{3} \cos A&=21 \\\ \cos A &= \frac{7}{4 \sqrt{3}} \\\ A &= \cos^{-1} \left(\frac{7}{4 \sqrt{3}}\right) \\\ &\approx 28.3^\circ. \end{aligned}$$

By the Law of Cosines, we have

$$\begin{aligned} (2 \sqrt{3})^2 &= (3 + \sqrt{3})^2 + \sqrt{6}^2 - 2 \cdot (3 + \sqrt{3}) \cdot \sqrt{6} \cos B \\\ 12 &= 17 + 6 \sqrt{3} - 12 \sqrt{3} \cos B \\\ 12 \sqrt{3} \cos B&=6 \\\ \cos B &= \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{3}} \\\ B &= \cos^{-1} \left(\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{3}}\right) \\\ &\approx 72.5^\circ. \end{aligned}$$

By the Triangle Angle Sum Theorem, we have

$$A + B + C = 180^\circ.$$ Solving for $C$, we get $$C = 180^\circ - A - B \approx 180^\circ - 28.3^\circ - 72.5^\circ = 79.2^\circ.$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{28.3^\circ, 72.5^\circ, 79.2^\circ}.$ I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
By the Law of Cosines, the cosine of one angle is
\begin{align*}
\frac{(3 + \sqrt{3})^2 + (2 \sqrt{3})^2 - (\sqrt{6})^2}{2 (3 + \sqrt{3})(2 \sqrt{3})} &= \frac{9 + 6 \sqrt{3} + 3 + 12 - 6}{4 \sqrt{3} (3 + \sqrt{3})} \\
&= \frac{18 + 6 \sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3} (12 + 4 \sqrt{3})} \\
&= \frac{3}{2 \sqrt{3}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
\end{align*}so this angle is $\boxed{30^\circ}.$

The cosine of another angle is
\begin{align*}
\frac{(3 + \sqrt{3})^2 + (\sqrt{6})^2 - (2 \sqrt{3})^2}{2 (3 + \sqrt{3})(\sqrt{6})} &= \frac{9 + 6 \sqrt{3} + 3 + 6 - 12}{6 \sqrt{2} + 6 \sqrt{6}} \\
&= \frac{6 + 6 \sqrt{3}}{6 \sqrt{2} + 6 \sqrt{6}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},
\end{align*}so this angle is $\boxed{45^\circ}.$

Then the third angle is $180^\circ - 30^\circ - 45^\circ = \boxed{105^\circ}.$
